Two things I wanna say here:\n\nFirst, thank you for reading all of this, and I genuinely hope that anything here has helped you in working with your ADHD, even if it's just a small, little thing.\n\nSecond, this twine is a work in progress, and might always be. It's not just that I want to make it look better, prettify the layout and UI, maybe add some more images, although I definitely do want to do all that. That 'First Edition' on the cover image there isn't just for show, I'd like to update this thing down the line.\n\nBut I also want to add more tips, techniques, and tools down the line. I specifically want to get in a chunk here on things I use specifically for dealing with ADHD as a writer. As you've seen me hammer over and over again in this twine, what works for me isn't guaranteed to work for everybody, and the same goes for you and others. Dealing with ADHD, just like so many other things, is something where we may share a lot of common traits but finding what helps us is not going to be an identical path, an identical set of tips and advice. I find that for dealing with ADHD, what helps a lot of us, especially since so many of us are likely to be unable to go to a doctor or get a prescription easily (or at all), is sharing with each other the little things we've done for ourselves to make things easier. If one technique, tip, trick, tool, strategy, whatever you wanna call it, doesn't work for us, it might still work for somebody else, or help us find our own methods of dealing with ADHD.\n\nI want to encourage that development and that sharing and discussion of tools and strategies. We share a lot of those jokes and comics and all that about living with ADHD, but when we find something that helps us, I want to encourage sharing those things, so that it might help someone else too, and they might help someone else, and so on and so forth. Recognizing the issues we have is a great first step, but all the better to share what we do to work with those issues, and help all of us have an easier time of things, even though we might still struggle anyway.\n\nSolidarity and strength with all of y'all. I hope this helps you, and I hope you help others in kind. Once again, thanks for reading all of this. Take care.\n\n-Colin Spacetwinks
[img[cover image][foreword]]
<center><h1>AUDIO/VIDEO STIMULUS ("I NEED TO BE DISTRACTED SO I CAN FOCUS")</h1>\n[img[distracted focus]]</center>\n\nSo, this one is going to take even more explanation than usual. For a lot of reasons, not least of which is because this - moreso than almost any of the other techniques - is going to be highly different from person to person on what works for them.\n\nLet's start with that root idea up there: "I need to be distracted so I can focus." This is how I've come to look at a lot of the tools I use to get things done but also as a way to better understand and explain to others the particulars of how my brain works. And to help explain why focus and productivity techniques that might be incredibly helpful to others can and often have been utterly disastrous for me.\n\nGood example: "Remove all distractions" is probably one of the most common tips you'll see in various self-help books or listicles or wikihows and so on about increasing your productivity. For a lot of people, this is actually something that is good to be reminded of! Many people will do worse if there's noise or other stimulus around them and will get a lot more done if they put themselves into some fairly silent and isolated work environment.\n\nFor me, and I suspect for many of you, doing this not only results in little to nothing getting done, it also ends up with stressing yourself the hell out. The lack of outside stimulus puts the mind into overdrive instead of in a peaceful and relaxed state, thoughts getting cluttered and frantic and then being frustrated with yourself with not getting anything done (especially after using such a common technique that's suppose to help so much).\n\nFor my experience with my ADHD, this is what leads me to "I need to be distracted so I can focus".\n\nYou can probably think of examples where this has been true for yourself already. Stimming devices, like fidget cubes and fidget spinners, or more improvised devices like a pocket full of change or a handful of dice. Something to keep yourself //occupied//, but not so much that it eats up your primary attention. Something a little more passive, taking up a chunk of your mind so the rest of it can keep focused on whats in front of it. Hell, people without ADHD will even use some of the same basic ideas here and there to help with work - having music on while you clean, playing a podcast as you go through chores, so on and so forth. It's just an issue, and tool to deal with that issue, that's far more acute within ADHD.\n\nIn essence, you need something to keep part of you busy, but just a little busy. Something that keeps your mind engaged, but not //too// engaged. You need to be distracted - so you can focus.\n\nThe how-to of this technique sounds simple enough: Put on some kind of audio - white noise, podcasts, music - or video on while you're doing work. What's tricky about it is trying to find the //precise// level of how distracting something should be, and the wild variations between what levels of distraction a person might need, and what might be too distracting for someone might not be distracting enough for another. This technique is very, very different from person to person. A lot of us will put on music while we work to help us get more work done, but the differences in what music we'd use to do that shifts wildly and not just due to what kind of personal musical taste we might have.\n\nLet's step back to look at this from a bit more abstract level again. A lot of us will focus, even unintentionally, on what gives us rapid or even instant feedback. Something we can engage with that will give us a response to our interacting with it at a fairly brisk pace. Knowing this helps me work out I would consider a good distraction, or a bad distraction.\n\nPeople talk bad about social media for all sorts of reasons, both valid ones and not, but I'v paid close attention to how twitter - specifically twitter - affects me and how I interact with it. Twitter is something that I'd absolutely call a 'bad distraction, but not because twitter can be a toxic cesspit. It's because of the specific ways it lights up my ADHD.\n\nTwitter is actually a //perfect// fit for my ADHD, like a hand in the world's coziest glove. It is //constant// stimulus. This isn't just in the potential dopamine rush of retweets and likes from making posts, but it's the stimulus of reading posts at all, and //always having more posts to read//. It auto-refreshes too, so I don't even need to hit that refresh button to get more content to read. Even if I never post myself, so long as I follow enough accounts, I am always getting more stimulus.\n\nOne could curate a twitter feed that has none of the usual social media toxicity at all and I'd still classify twitter as a 'bad distraction', because everything about it is set up in a way to be too //actively// distracting, and constantly so. If you try to multi-task scrolling around twitter and doing some other work, you might make some progress... but you'll also likely end up with a ratio of time spent on each that's heavily lopsided in favor of 'scrolling through twitter'. This has happened to me before, still happens to me now, will happen to me again. It's just a really good distraction, and the socialization aspect (especially for most people under quarantine, and furthermore for people with more circumstances that isolate them) also makes it hard to ignore. Shit will chew up your time, your attention, and your mental energy and make it very hard to shift to the work you want to do and staying focused on it.\n\nIn terms of 'good distractions'? I have all sorts! Notably, most of them are fairly passive experiences. I mentioned white noise and music already, but I also have surprising amounts of video I'll put on while I'm working to keep one part of my head busy so the rest of it can focus on work. Hell, as I write this, I have a video of Giant Bomb playing in a shrunk down window, to the side of all this text. But I can't just use any music or any video while I write. They still have to fit certain criteria to become passive instead of active distractions.\n\nWhite noise and the like is a bit simpler. You put on some white noise (or pink noise, or brown noise, or etc, etc) and you see if it helps you focus or not. If it does, it does, if it doesn't, it doesn't. When it comes to things like music and video, the sheer enormous variety of content and different potential personal reactions to them can be overwhelming.\n\nSo let's talk how I tend to sort these things out for myself. I'll use video first. The most common kinds of video I put on while I work are ones I've already watched a million times before, so much so that I could probably recreate the whole thing in my head. That way, when I actually put the video on, it's hitting just the right level of stimulus for me. Something that's providing background audio and visual stimulus for me but not so much I have to actually pay attention to it to know what's happening. This is why I'm using a Giant Bomb video at this moment as I write, and also specifically using one I've already watched several times before. When I already know the content so well I can engage with it passively, it becomes primo 'good distraction material', which is why I've almost never used brand new videos from Giant Bomb for this purpose. Too many unknowns, too much stimulus, too much need for me to pay attention to it to know what's happening.\n\nAnother good example of how this works for me is if I put on anime while I work. While I'll usually opt for subs over dubs in anime, if I'm writing or doing other work, it //has// to be dubs. Subs require me to read, which means more active engagement, which means pulling too much of my attention away from the primary thing I'm trying to focus on and trying to use anime to keep the part of my brain that needs constant stimulus busy so I can focus. And just as I wouldn't use a new video from Giant Bomb while I'm working, I also am almost certain to never put on an anime I've never seen before, dubs or otherwise, while I write.\n\nThe number one kind of video I'll put on while I'm doing something else is any one of about two dozen episodes of Mystery Science Theater 3000. I've watched a lot of MST3K, and I've watched some episodes an astonishing amount of times, so now I'll throw one of those up to provide a nice bit of passive distraction so the active part of my mind can go to work elsewhere.\n\nSame ideas apply to audio, to music, although this area will require more personal experimentation than probably any other technique I could offer. Maybe just using some white noise does the trick for you. Or maybe some music. Or maybe playing music and white noise at the same time. And what //kind// of music helps you focus and what kind distracts you too much will vary wildly from person to person. What works for me might not work at all for you - you'll wanna go through some trial and error here, but a way to narrow down the options would be to think about what kind of sound you know gets what kind of response from you. Like what music you can //passively// engage with, and what kind you //actively// engage with.\n\nUsing myself as an example: I'll sometimes use music, or white noise, or both together, but what kind of music is particular. Usually I'll opt towards music without lyrics, heavy on electronic stuff like Justice or Daft Punk - lots of looping rhythms. But there are songs with lyrics I can and will use as a good passive distraction, but just like my choice of video to play, I require it to be songs I am so familiar with that I don't think about them at all. And generally, I'll loop just those one or two songs while I work instead of a whole playlist, making the music become a kind of white noise itself. A specific example is putting Paramore's "Hard Times" on a singular loop in my headphones for a several hours as I wrote. Got thousands of words done that day. This result is not guaranteed or anything, mind you, it's just an example of the methodology.\n\nThere is one particular group of songs I like to point to when it comes to engaging with my ADHD, parsing out how my own mental processes work to myself and explaining them to others, figuring out how my mind works and how to stimulate it properly to get the results I want:\n\nNeil Cicerega's trilogy of mashup albums, Mouth Silence, Mouth Moods, and Mouth Sounds.\n\nFor most people, I think these albums would be unbelievably awful for focusing on work. Just the worst. A mass collection of noise, throwing together completely unrelated songs in bizarre ways, especially ones like "Piss" or "Shit" which have about six or so significantly different songs being sampled throughout and rearranged the entire time.\n\nFor me, they are absolutely fantastic for getting work done.\n\nOne way I've described how ADHD works for me is that it's a lot like falling into a wikipedia hole inside of your own brain. A constant game of "Six Degrees Of". One thing connects to another thing which connects to another thing which so on and so forth, a rapidly lighting up trail of thoughts that if you only showed the Start and the End points wouldn't make any sense at all to people. But for you, it was just jumping from one related subject to the next, with a different related subject being the next jumping off point from there.\n\nHere's a quick example for how it can work out inside my head:\n\nBrian Michael Bendis (comic book writer) -> Spider-Man (Bendis wrote many Spider-Man comics, most well known for Ultimate Spider-Man) -> Tom DeFalco (also a comic book writer, also worked on Spider-Man, including The Clone Saga, which was a major adapted arc in Ultimate Spider-Man too) -> G.I. Joe (Tom DeFalco was a major part of the creative team for the 80s relaunch of the property) -> The Military-Industrial Complex (G.I. Joe as a superheroic interpretation of the American military and thus in part glamorizing said military, helping fuel positive perception of it) -> The F-35 Jet (one of the most expensive ongoing projects for the American military and an oft cited example of how the Military-Industrial Complex works, with new funds constantly going into military contractors no matter how much the end product doesn't work)\n\nFrom one comic book writer to the F-35 jet. Like I said, if you look just at the start and the finish, it doesn't make any sense. But if you see each connection made along the way, the journey might still be a strange one, but you can understand how I got there. Just like falling down that wikipedia hole, clicking on one related article, then another related article, then another related article...\n\nSo, what does this have to do with Neil Cicierega and how I use his mashup albums for focus?\n\nIt's that an awful lot of that music tickles at that exact part of my brain. It not only plays into that need for passive engagement while I put active engagement elsewhere, but having so wildly different famous songs (and often so many different songs at once) being pressed together, it hits the specific way I arrange a train of thought. That it sets it to a rhythmic beat, all the better, because that level of predictability and familiarity makes it easier to keep it as a passive distraction instead of an active one.\n\nThese albums, of course, won't work for everyone! Not just because ADHD is different for everyone, but because the social context for this trilogy of albums is heavily based on American pop culture, and that's only gonna go so far. But even if the albums themselves aren't the kind of music that will help you specifically, I think understanding the //way// they help me as I work can help you do the same for yourself - analyzing how your brain puts thoughts together, how it responds to certain kinds of stimuli, and from there being able to narrow down what kinds of distractions are the best for you, personally. 'More noise' isn't always going to be a downside if the kind of noise in question is well tailored to your own thinking patterns.\n\n[[PREVIOUSLY: THE DIGITAL TIMER|the digital timer]] | [[NEXT: THE TO-DO LIST|to do list]]

[[FOREWORD|foreword]]\n\n<h1>PART 1</h1>\n[[THE KITCHEN TIMER|the kitchen timer]]\n\n[[THE DIGITAL TIMER|the digital timer]]\n\n[[AUDIO/VIDEO STIMULUS|audio video]]\n\n[[THE TO-DO LIST|to do list]]\n\n<h1>PART 2</h1>\n[[EXERCISE|exercise]]\n\n[[PERSONAL ORGANIZATION|room]]\n\n[[BASIC HUMAN NEEDS (FOOD, WATER, ETC)|basic human needs]]\n\n<h1>FINAL PART</h1>\n[[ENDING|ending]]
<center><h1>EXERCISE</h1></center>\n\nOkay, first off and straight up: Fuck any shit that tells you you gotta lose weight or whatever. I will never tell you that you've gotta be any particular body shape or weight for this shit because all that advice is absolutely horseshit.\n\nExercise, for me, is a physical act done to help deal with mental shit. Practicalities and pragmatics, and absolutely no benefits I get from exercise has or ever will be pointing towards dropping weight, like so much wellness shit will tell you. I'm very firm and repetitive on this because it's very important to me to stand against what so many will say about your own mental well being and what kind of weight and body you should have to have it. Fuck all that shit.\n\nFor me, when I'm exercising - especially and particularly for dealing with my own ADHD - my goal is to work up a sweat. That's it. It is not to do a certain specific exercise or a certain amount of reps or burn a certain amount of calories. It is just to get to a point where I've worked up a sweat. After that, I feel pretty good that I can stop, though sometimes I'll go a little while longer.\n\nThe reasons for having 'just work up a sweat' as my end goal for exercise? I have two in mind.\n\nThe first is that exercise can release chemicals inside you that help with all that brain shit. People will say "maybe you should exercise more" or "have you tried yoga" as some weak attempt as a cure-all. And it's not. Will never be. You almost certainly already know this and sneer at people telling you to try them to deal with the shit fucking you up.\n\nAnd I sneer too, even as I use exercise myself as one tool to help with my focus issues. That bit right there is important - exercise is ''one tool'' to help with my focus issues. It is not a cure-all, it is simply a tool, and it is one among many. For some, exercise won't help att all! And that's fine! None of the tools and techniques we use are there to fix everything, they are just exactly that: tools and techniques. We use them to help ourselves, and we do our best to figure out what works for us, what doesn't, and what sort of works and how we might best adjust it.\n\nSo, the first benefit of exercise for me is just purely helpful chemical release. Help your brain unleash those mental connectors that come with a sweat. The second benefit, for me, is coming at the same area the kitchen timer does: forcing yourself into ''do shit'' mode.\n\nBuilding up a sweat by doing just some basic cardio - running in place, jumping in place, dancing, whatever, you name it - helps me take myself out of the 'an object at rest stays at rest' status. Just like so many of these other techniques, it's about slicing through that block where you are feeling permanently on the precipice of doing something, but cannot execute. It's different than the purity of a "But I don't want to" impulse for not getting something done, Active procrastination is a wildly different beast than "God I want to fucking get this thing done but I feel utterly stuck here".\n\nI use this same shit for my depression as well. It doesn't cure anything there, but when I can work myself to the point that I make myself start building up that sweat, it helps punch through that status quo of "I am not, and will not be, getting anything done, no matter how much I want to".\n\nThis is not to say any of this is easy, far from it. Hell, I use other ADHD management techniques to help enable this one. I'll bust out the kitchen timer to force myself into that do shit mode for exercising, and from there use that combined momentum from both of them to do other things I want and/or need to do. People say "Just exercise!" as a well meant but unintentionally condescending piece of advice because to so many it's something that you would 'just' do and not something that requires far more mental energy expended to even start doing it than flicking a mental switch, like flipping a coding tag of "exercise:false" to "exercise:true".\n\nExercise has helped me - in specific circumstances, with specific purposes, and it is not something easily done. So when I say 'exercise might help', know I'm saying it without wanting a single thing to do with the way it's almost always sold to you, me, and others.\n\nSo if you're gonna try exercise, just focus on working up a sweat and putting that exercise into a specific purpose. You ain't gotta get fit or have any goals or intentions or desires at all towards 'getting fit' to get benefits from exercise. You don't have to do super intense, heavily designed routines to get that sweat up either. A good example - and also exercise being used to help with other brain garbage, depression - would be Alex Navarro at Giant Bomb. We've chatted before about things we do to work with our depression, I brought up the lil things I've done with exercise to help me out, and he has done the same - not with an workout routine, not with complex machines, and not even with clothes and gear made with exercise in mind. He works up a sweat from drumming. And believe me, as someone who doesn't drum, even just air-drumming to some intense metal music or the like can work up a sweat inside you after a couple of songs.\n\nNo need to go for miles long runs, no need to sign up for a gym, no need to build routines that you try to stick to day after day, week after week. If you wanna see if doing a little exercise might help you with breaking through these blocks that our brain put up, all you gotta do is spend some minutes working up a bit of a sweat. And if it doesn't work out for you? Well, as with all the other pieces and techniques suggested here, that's fine. You find what works, what doesn't, adapt and discard as necessary. If exercise doesn't give ya shit for benefits, don't sweat moving onto something else to see if it helps you.\n\n[[PREVIOUSLY: TO DO LIST|to do list]] | [[NEXT: PERSONAL ORGANIZATION|room]]
<center><h1>THE TO-DO LIST ("ORDER OF OPERATIONS")</h1></center>\n\nAh. The dreaded to-do list. The tool we are most told to use and perhaps the one we find most impossible to use. "Just write out what you gotta do and do it!"\n\nBut we can't focus ourselves enough to write the list at all.\n\nI've struggled with to-do lists, often still do. Especially thanks to having not just ADHD but also depression and anxiety, to-do lists can be a real landmine of issues, causing stress to spike while you're trying to take on a technique that's supposed to make things //less// stressful. Or even just the difficulty of remembering to use to-do lists, that's a motherfucker that only so much mindfulness can deal with.\n\nSo why would I think to-do lists are worth my time at all?\n\nComes down to changing the way to-do lists are used, the way we perceive them and why we're filling them out in the first place. On first glance, a to-do list is exactly that: a list of tasks. Stuff you have to do for any particular project or day or whatever.\n\nA list of //obligations//.\n\nAnd looked at as a list of obligations, it is immediately stressful to me. Thinking about the obligations is stressful, writing them down and looking at them is incredibly stressful, and the focus issues from my ADHD get exacerbated by the stress and impulses that my depression and anxiety bring up, working in tandem to make it harder to write all the goals out, much less complete them. And if they're things that really, truly are obligations? Things I have to get done in a specific time limit, not things I can get around to when I feel like it? Even worse! The anxiety spikes, the stress spikes, which means the focus issues get worse. Everything collapses into each other which amplifies every other aspect to make doing things harder, and the longer things are put off, the more stressful and harder to focus it gets. It's like if the core of a snowball rolling down a hill was made out of knots. All these interwoven factors that affect each other, and it just gets worse and worse the longer it goes on.\n\nSo how can this bullshit actually be useful for me getting anything done?\n\nChanging the perspective on to-do lists is what ended up seeing not only what use they had for me, but also giving me better insight into the ways my mind works for me, the way my thoughts are structured and what to do with them.\n\nThe short version is this: I took the to-do list, that list of obligations, and turned it into an ''order of operations''.\n\nIt goes back to one of the issues I brought up when talking about the kitchen timer. One of the things you're struggling with a to-do list is doing the to-do list at all, which the kitchen timer can help with - but it's the thing the kitchen timer is specifically affecting, and customizing the to-do list for that. I talked about the mind being in a kind of overflow state, bouncing around information and constantly //thinking// instead of //doing//, and how the kitchen timer acts a kind of circuit breaker, allowing you to reset your own thoughts.\n\nThe to-do list as I use it is targeting that same cluster of problems. It's not about making a list of things to-do, per se, it's about getting all the thoughts //out// of your brain, and into something physical, tangible. The first thing you're doing is not actually writing down the tasks you have to do, it's in emptying out your own damn skull, like releasing a pressure valve on your brain. From there, it's being able to organize the thoughts you let seep out of your head into that ''order of operations'' so you can firmly know what to do first and what comes after that.\n\nIt's that thing I mentioned of walking back and forth from room to room because you have two interrelated tasks and thus just keep keep pacing and thinking instead of doing. Techniques to help you switch from thinking to doing are helpful on their own, sure, but I enhance this with the to-do list by having a firm point of reference of what I will do //first//. It's building off the circuit breaker idea, making it so I not only reset my brain so the thoughts aren't cluttered, but getting the thoughts out so they're not eating up all my mental energy, and then arranging a clear line of thoughts so I don't get back into a loop. "These are all the things I have to do today" is overwhelming, on the written page, but especially while it's just swirling around in our head, building up energy and amping up stress. "This is the thing I have to do first, and then I can do this next thing, which allows me to do this thing". Order of operations. A series of unlocks instead of a giant fuck-off list of "LOOK AT ALL THIS SHIT YOU GOTTA DO" all at once.\n\nLet's give an incredibly specific micro-example of how order of operations, and how it can get scrambled - one I've done just myself this week.\n\n"I want something to drink. I'm going to take the glass that's already in my room, go to the kitchen, and fill that glass with what I want to drink."\n\nNow, most of us won't spell out every little step in our head that way. On average, I'd say the majority of us keep it to something like 'I'm thirsty' or 'I'm gonna get a drink'. But laying it all out like this will help give some context around how our brains can fuck it up, and how a to-do list made with that context in mind can help.\n\nThe order of operations here can easily, and quickly, become a horrible mess. What should be an easy task becomes a mess as each piece of the whole gets disconnected from each other, becoming a jumble in the mind as you pace back and forth from your room to the kitchen and back again. You'll go to the kitchen to get a drink, but ah, you forgot your glass, so you go back to your room to get the glass, but then you forget why you were getting a glass or get detoured by some other thought. So then you eventually go back to the kitchen, either because you remembered 'I want to get a drink' or because you remembered 'I know I have to go into the kitchen to get //something//.' So then you go to the kitchen, and perhaps this whole process loops, or you do get a drink - but you forgot to bring your glass, so you get a new glass, and fill it, and bring it back to your room.\n\nExtend this out over a week. Now you have 11 glasses in your room.\n\nOr, here's another example, a common, small one for me, but still very devilishly good at eating up my time and energy without getting anything done.\n\nI mentioned the act of staring at the dishes in the sink and still not getting them done at all when talking about using the kitchen timer. An addendum here: staring at the dishes in the sink, and thinking //I need to put the dishes here into the dishwasher// which runs into //But the dishwasher is full. So I need to empty the dishwasher.// Now, lotta people would naturally think "okay, so... empty the dishwasher. what's the problem here"\n\nBut I know for me, and others, it's a lot of bouncing back between those two thoughts and not doing either of them. The mind just loops. "I need to do dishes" and "But I need to empty the dishwasher" and then to "But I need to do the dishes" and then back to "But I need to empty the dishwasher", and still not getting any forward momentum on either of them.\n\nYou'll likely find that you've had struggles like this, or hell, exactly like these examples. It applies for tasks big and small. What should be one whole thought process explodes and becomes several pieces, which then will bounce around in our head and have us jumping from one to the other, struggling to remember what thought we had before, and then when we remember that one, trying to remember the ones that we just had in our head that were distracting us from remembering that other thought.\n\nFun!\n\nSo, the to-do list is first to establish that order of operations, that firm decision of what you will do ''first'', and what comes after that. To firmly decide the ''first'' thing is ''I will do the dishes'' and then the ''second'' thing you will do is ''I will empty the dishwasher''. Establishing not only that you will switch from thinking to doing - which is what that kitchen timer is for - but being able to set down exactly what it is you're going to do first and foremost, so as to be able to do the tasks afterwards. Order of operations. \n\nAnd then by writing it down, having those thoughts ''out of your head'' and ''into a physical form''. We use a to-do list as a holding place for our thoughts and a place we can organize them, keeping them from eating up all the time and energy in our head as we fight with ourselves to chain it together into one clear process.\n\nThis whole thing is also why I specifically prefer a physical to-do list where possible. Firstly so I can just carry it around with me and refer to it - and scrawl into it - whenever and wherever necessary, and also simply because of the way it works better for me mentally. Something about the physical action of writing all these things down helps me more than it does when I type it in digitally. I've tried to explain it in words several times here, and I still feel a bit unconfident if I've gotten it across, so... here. A very amateur visual representation of how this whole process feels and acts for me.\n\n<center>[img[garbage brain 1]]\n\n[img[garbage brain 2]]\n\n[img[garbage brain 3]]</center>\n\nDoes that make sense? I really hope it does.\n\nOne other thing: The timing of when I employ the to-do list is pretty crucial to me too. Might just be because I also have anxiety and depression, but maybe you too suffer from the heightened stress levels that come when you make your to-do list too far in advance. I tend to think 'shit, I should make a to-do list' when I'm already starting to feel that spiral of messy thoughts come over me. This falls right into the goal of making an order of operations, not a list of obligations. Like the images above point to, I'm using this to spill my brain out onto something I can actually grasp and physically rearrange as needed so it's not eating up all my mental energy. Putting together the list way before I need to actually do anything - for me anyway - can often create a whole bunch of anxieties and stresses and ends up making an unhelpful thought spiral instead of helping ending one. It takes time to build that kind of personal mental alarm system to start thinking "Shit, I should dump this out of my brain and onto paper" when you start pacing back and forth and looping in thoughts, but it's a mental routine I definitely suggest spending some time working on.\n\nIt might be totally different for you, but if you've got the same struggles I do, then hopefully this framing helps!\n\nAs ever, adjust all of this as needed for yourself!\n\n[[PREVIOUSLY: AUDIO VIDEO STIMULATION|audio video]] | [[NEXT: EXERCISE|exercise]]

32yltvvXXDrbfeuuGGG27YtHXr1nsfeuihxx566MHH7rzztns3b9iw4c4777zstttuW7tly5ZlO3bsOKehoeHsxsbGM524EgcOHDhw4OBfGf8LZb22vYlJWusAAAAASUVORK5CYII=
This twine, this collection of my own tips, tricks, and thoughts of how I try to deal with my own ADHD is something I’ve wanted to do for a good long while now, but like any good project being considered by someone with ADHD, took entirely too much time to commit to doing it in the first place. Which wasn’t because I secretly didn’t want to do it. I genuinely really have been wanting to put together something like this for awhile, especially as I kept making twitter threads that shared a ton of my techniques on dealing with ADHD in the first place. Having a place where it’s all collected together and each technique can be contextualized by others would only make it all better, as well as easier for people to find, download, and reference as necessary.\n\nBut what really put me over the edge on getting this started at all - other than remembering to use my own techniques in the first place - was this comic that got around on twitter a bit ago. Don’t remember who made it, maybe someone could help me out here. But it was someone looking at a comic or meme or something about Relatable ADHD behavior and responding “Haha, I do that!” And then there’s a beat. Followed by the last panel:\n\n“What do I do with this information?”\n\nWhat I’ve seen a lot lately is that many of us are getting better at identifying our ADHD, what behaviors we have in it, how it messes with our focus, our ability to get tasks started and finished, but people are struggling to take that knowledge and turn it into something they could use to help with their ADHD. Which, no surprise, one of ADHD’s core, most frequent problems it presents to those who have it is getting things started or finished at all, and that includes doing things to tackle the ADHD itself.\n\nI wanted to help people make that move, from knowing things about your ADHD, to being better able to do things about it. We share around a lot of videos and images and all of “this is what ADHD is like”, and, y’know, it’s funny and all, it’s nice to have a mutual laugh at the shit we gotta deal with, but we all know it’s only so much help. It gives us some catharsis, but it’s not helping us get ahead and get more done, and a lot of people are looking for ways to get there.\n\nThese are things that helped me, and I share them in the hopes that they’ll help you. There’s no guarantees here that they’ll fix your problems, hell, I can’t even guarantee that they’ll all help you, or help you as much or in the exact same way that they’ve helped me. We can find common traits in ADHD across people, but we still have different experiences with it, and what helps one person might not help another. It’s like meds. What pills work out marvelously for me might do absolutely nothing for someone else, and vice versa.\n\nThis is not to instill hopelessness - quite the opposite. One thing you’ll see me repeat a lot through here is taking these various techniques with the approach of “I HAVE to use these” or “If they don’t work for me then it’s all POINTLESS” is of no help to anyone. Dealing with your ADHD, dealing with a lot of the self in general, is something that takes experimentation, that takes adaptation and trial and error because everyone has different shit going on inside of them. The goal is to not aim for a ‘fix’, for everything to become a total 180 on your focus issues, because that sets you up for frustration and disappointment and even perhaps a sense of inevitable failure.\n\nI offer these tips, tricks, and techniques with this approach to them in mind for you: These helped me, I hope they help you. Some of them might, some might not. Use what works, adapt and modify what requires it, discard what doesn’t work for you at all. You may very well come across or develop different techniques entirely that help you much better than mine do! Which is great! What I’m doing here is just sharing what I’ve got that works pretty well for me, and hoping it helps you, and even if it doesn’t, that it helps you get to a place of better understanding your ADHD, how it affects you, how you react to it, so you can be in a better position to develop your own tools to work with it.\n\nI said earlier, but I’ll say it again with some expansion: I’ll repeat those kind of thoughts multiple times in this twine, as well as others. Part of this is simply because I’m my own editor here, and I’m not a very good one. The other part of it is sometimes you just need to have the same piece of knowledge bashed against your head a few times rather bluntly before you can really start absorbing it. If it’s so easy for us to forget why we came into the living room for something, then it’s not much of a stretch to think that some repetition of concepts might help a little to settle those concepts into our head.\n\nWhatever it is you do, I hope I can give you even just a little help with getting it done and getting a better understanding and handling of your ADHD.\n\n-Colin Spacetwinks\n\n[[NEXT: THE KITCHEN TIMER|the kitchen timer]]

<center><h1>BASIC HUMAN NEEDS (FOOD, WATER, POSSIBLY DEALING WITH ALLERGENS, ETC)</h1></center>\n\nThis one, like the piece about exercise, is a bit tricky because much like the exercise piece, this is an area where we have gotten an awful lot of advice that has felt like well meant but condescending platitudes that don’t actually help us.\n\nBut, also like exercise, there are spaces and contexts where this advice can and does help us with dealing with our shit. It’s just never in the way it’s pitched to us.\n\n“Drink more water” or “Stay hydrated” is a good place to start. It is something we have all been fed an exhausting amount of times when talking about our issues or just getting it out of nowhere as we roll through the internet in general, and it’s very easy to roll our eyes at it. I know I do. It gets pitched to us as something that will fix our shit. Like a crappy ad on the side of a website telling us “ONE WEIRD TRICK TO SOLVE ALL YOUR INABILITY TO DO THE TASKS FACING YOU RIGHT NOW” in red text on a black background, followed by a low res jpeg of a water bottle. It’s not helpful. It’s annoying, and frequently, it’s demoralizing too. Because we’ll drink that water, we’ll stay hydrated and hey, what the fuck, I still have a shitload of problems.\n\nBut I’ll say this right now. Drinking water does help. Staying hydrated does help. And that word choice is very important.\n\nIt //helps//. It doesn’t //fix// things. It just //helps//.\n\nLet’s use a practical example, because everything here at its core is in fact a practical problem, just ones we have seeing in such a fashion. Let’s say you have a headache. And on top of having a headache, you have a job or some chores to do. You need to stack some shelves or clean some floors or wash some dishes or fill out some paperwork. Take your pick, you can think of plenty more things you’ve gotta do on the regular. That headache is going to make doing any of that work harder. Pain will bother you, distract you, and sap your overall energy from whatever it is you have to do. So, in order to relieve pain and be able to have more energy and focus on the tasks before you, you take some headache medicine.\n\nThe headache medicine isn’t going to fix any other problems you had before with trying to deal with that work. You’re still going to have focus issues. You’re still going to have trouble with getting tasks started and sticking to them. Taking a tylenol, an advil, a store brand headache pill, none of it is going to fix those problems, it’s not designed for that shit.\n\nBut taking care of a headache means there’s still //one less// thing to bother you, distract you, drain your energy, and make your work harder than it has to be for yourself.\n\nIt’s the same for hydration. Hell, since dehydration can also cause headaches, it’s even more similar than you might think at first.\n\nWhen it comes to basic physical needs and your ADHD, that perspective, that context, must be kept in mind. It’s crucial to moving away from a Pass/Fail perspective on one’s own skills, personal growth, or completion of basic day to day chores and into a perspective that will actually help you get things done and take better care of yourself. And taking care of yourself will help you do a better job of getting things done, and getting things done will help you do a better job of taking care of yourself. //Better//, not //fixed//. There will still be problems. There will still be days where you struggle to get shit done. Even if you did something that I haven’t pulled off, sticking to using all these tips and tricks every single day, you would still have those struggles, those rough days.\n\nAnd that’s //fine//. The goal is not to ‘fix’ everything, to have a permanent transformation and everything just works now. It is to get better. It is to make things //easier// on yourself. You will never be at a point where you never have problems ever again with getting things done. That is not a failure of the self, of our skills, of our efforts. It is just what we’re working with. And once we move past that Pass/Fail way of looking at what we do and how much of it we do, it gets much easier //to// do any of those things, and to do things that will in turn make doing other things easier as well.\n\nRemembering to stay hydrated, to drink plenty of water, is just one example, though it is a very good one. If you haven’t drank enough water, you have less energy to do anything, even thinking straight. It’s useful to think of a lot of our practical human needs as either fuel or things that affect how much of that fuel we burn. If you haven’t eaten enough (or at all) or you haven’t drank enough water (or also at all), then any task you try to put yourself with will be you doing work with a sub-optimal amount of energy, or outright running on fumes. Which makes getting the task done harder, which makes us more frustrated with ourselves for not being able to get the task done, which… you get the idea. It’s a dangerous potential spiral, a snowball of mental and physical drain that only makes it harder over time to get things done the longer it goes on. Something that felt difficult to begin with will feel progressively harder, perhaps even outright impossible, the longer you try to tackle that problem while running on a dry mouth and an empty stomach.\n\nSo it goes for things beyond just ‘I should drink water’ or ‘I should eat food’ and ‘Hm, I should probably get a big thing of multivitamins, and especially a bottle of vitamin D if I don’t get outside much’. One big one that has had a big impact on the total amount of energy and focus I have to put towards things I want or need to do is finally account for allergies affecting me.\n\nFor the longest time, I didn’t think I had allergies, because I didn’t sneeze all the time, didn’t have that scratchy throat, didn’t have all the usual symptoms that allergy commercials would bring up. I ‘only’ tended to have lots of backed up mucus in my throat as well as just lower energy overall. The latter I could reasonably attribute to depression, which I already knew I had. But once I started taking allergy meds and doing shit in my personal space to account for allergies… well, I still had depression and ADHD of course.\n\nBut I had //much// more energy to deal with them.\n\nActually taking allergy meds, even just over the counter ones, helped plenty, sure, but it was also an aspect of cleaning I never much got around to even when I did get myself to the point of cleaning at all: dusting. Going over my whole room, my whole workspace, and just dusting the hell out of everything had a much greater effect than simply making things look or ‘feel’ nicer. I had more energy for my work. I was sleeping better, which also gave me more energy for my work. This wasn’t a fix-all of course, as I’ve mentioned, I still had depression and ADHD. Those are things I still did, still do, have to wrangle with every day.\n\nBut dealing with those allergies, clearing out all that dust, still gave me a great personal improvement in my capabilities, my stamina, to deal with myself and the tasks at hand. Nothing you address with your body is going to ‘fix’ things, not even getting pills specifically for ADHD or other brain shit. I am fortunate enough to not only have a prescription for my ADHD, but the prescription also seems to work pretty decently for me. It still doesn’t //fix// the issues my ADHD gives me, but it does make things //easier// for me.\n\nWater, food, vitamins, the potential that allergens are dragging you down and you don’t even know it as I didn’t for years, all of these are things you can take on to make your struggles with ADHD easier, to make the tools and techniques you do use more effective overall. None of them on their own or even all together will give you the complete turn-around in functionality and output that we so often desire and are just as often told is necessary or the only true measure of ‘success’ or ‘progress’. But when you’re dealing with ADHD, depression, or any other number of internal issues that might be messing with you, addressing the physical issues that could exacerbate the problems and sap your energy to work on them will give you better results during those struggles. And will also help you avoid more of those pitfalls, those spirals of ‘not getting anything done because I have no energy’ and ‘no energy because I’m not getting anything done’.\n\nEven if you end up on a day where you address all these purely physical issues and still don’t get anything done because of your ADHD, you’re still doing good for yourself, because imagine how much more difficult that day, and the days to follow from there, would be if you //hadn’t// dealt with those physical issues. You have more energy leftover at the end of the day, which’ll help you have more energy tomorrow, too. Doing what you can to avoid ending up running on fumes means less and less exhaustion, which is good for anything and everything you could put yourself to. Doing what you can to have the highest physical and mental stamina you have will always be good for you, //even when you still don’t get anything done.// Avoiding burnout and exhaustion and worse spirals is just as important to dealing with your ADHD as anything else.\n\nTo wrap up, I’ll get a little bit more specific on food and what I do to help with it for myself. First off, when they say breakfast is the most important meal of the day, they aren’t kidding. For reasons that are very obvious but also easy to just let slip out of your mind: You can’t do anything without fuel, breakfast is the start of the day, and if you try to do things all day without getting any fuel in you first, it’s going to suck. It’s possible to get things done on an empty stomach, to run on fumes, but it’s never the ideal situation. If at all possible, you always want to get plenty of that food and water in the morning, even if you have trouble remembering to stay hydrated and fed through the rest of the day. \n\nI keep a few things in mind for what I’m looking to get from food, generally - protein, fiber, carbs, and where possible, convenience. Just like with exercise before it, I don’t care about losing weight, or ever framing ‘healthy’ eating in that context. Eating healthily, eating for your well being, got jack shit to do with weight. I might be a broken record on this (and other things) but I feel it’s very important to reinforce this, since we’re constantly told day in and day out otherwise.\n\nWith protein, fiber, and carbs, what I’m essentially trying to get from a meal, especially breakfast, is having energy, having energy to burn, and having that energy go a long way. I am extremely not a dietician, so anyone who is, feel free to correct me, but this is how I lay it out for myself: Protein helps with energy overall but is especially important for muscles and the maintenance thereof, carbs are very important for the general pool of energy you’ll have to draw from for anything you have to or want to do, and fiber will help you feeling full for longer.\n\nKeeping all that in mind as well as the factor of convenience, which can be crucial when we’re running low on time, or don’t have much energy to begin with, or are just struggling to focus on putting together a meal in general, my go-to breakfast is: Greek yogurt, high fiber oatmeal, and a banana. Greek yogurt provides the high amount of early morning protein and is easy enough to get, be it from a large tub or in individual packages. High fiber oatmeal of course brings around the fiber and is a pretty easy breakfast food to throw together. Both’ll give me some needed morning carbs. The banana has a fair amount of carbs, but it also has a fourth piece which is not as important as those first three, but I still like to make sure I get where I can: Potassium. It’s an important part of electrolytes which… help generate the electricity in your body. A banana is a nice, cheap, and convenient way to get one of the big refreshing benefits that you’d get from things like Gatorade, but without having to go buy and drink a bunch of Gatorade. This breakfast is relatively cheap for what it delivers (and you can use regular yogurt to also get plenty of the benefits at a lower price, if need be), covers a lot of the bases you need for energy that you’ll have to expend throughout the day, and crucially is pretty easy, fast, and convenient to assemble in the morning when our energy and focus might be low to begin with.\n\nAnd, of course, water. Staying hydrated is still crucial.\n\nThese options of course will not be available to everyone, for a variety of reasons, including those who are vegan. But that’s fine, you can just see what I’m doing with food for myself as a basic template to draw from for however you want/need to assemble food to address your needs. That base of focusing on protein, fiber, and carbs (with a side of potassium) has gone a long way of helping me have energy to do anything at all, day to day. Doesn’t have to be physical things, either. Even just thinking about things will eat up energy, and you don’t want to be running on fumes for that either. Refilling your stamina at the start of the day will make things a hell of a lot easier on yourself, even if things still end up not going well. You want to address things that could take existing problems and make them //worse//, and do what you can to patch ‘em up. You’ll still have the problems, sure! But the problems won’t be as draining as they could’ve been, which makes it easier to keep dealing with the problems from there, not just in one day, but the next day too. Building yourself up, bit by bit, instead of that Pass/Fail perspective that so often leads to us undercutting ourselves.\n\nAfter all, a lot of us have self-medicated for ADHD with caffeine. Tons of people without ADHD will struggle to get shit done without some caffeine. If you’ve thought ‘ugh I can’t get anything done till I get some caffeine in me’, extend that to food and water as well.\n\nDealing with ADHD might still be hard, but we don’t need to make it harder for ourselves than it has to be. If you're feeling like shit, run down, struggling to get things done, take a moment to stop and think to yourself "Have I forgotten to eat enough? Have I forgotten to drink enough water?", and if it turns out to be the case that you have forgotten to do that - go eat! Go hydrate! Whatever problem you're facing will not get any easier by letting yourself go hungry and dehydrated! Do not worry about 'fixing' things, just do what you can to not let your problems be any harder for yourself than they have to be.\n\n[[PREVIOUSLY: PERSONAL ORGANIZATION|room]] | [[NEXT: ENDING|ending]]
ADHD Tips, tricks, and techniques
<center><h1>PERSONAL ORGANIZATION</h1></center>\n\nI'm gonna lay out the tip itself before diving into the why here. Blunt and straightforward:\n\n''You want all the shit you need for your work, for your life, to be as visible as possible.''\n\nI'm most likely gonna have to emphasize and re-emphasize that a few times because the advice I've been given, that just about everyone has been given, about best organization practices has generally been of no help to me and sometimes (frequently?) made things worse. Harder to work, harder to build routines, harder to get anything done at all. Even doing things I like for fun. The core of that advice which has done no good for me and so many others is something to the tune of:\n\n''Put everything in a nice neat box or folder, and then put that box or folder somewhere where you can't see it.''\n\nThis is a very common kind of advice for organization, and thing is, it's not 'bad', per se, but it's bad for me. It's bad for a lot of us. It actually works for a lot of people, helps a lot of people, to have everything put away in nice neat organized spaces that are then put away in something else that's out of your field of view. Plenty of people work far better with these more standard ideas of organization, where having everything in sight will hinder their ability to focus, to get work done or to work for very long.\n\nIt does not work for me, though, and I'll bet it doesn't work for a lot of you reading this either. I've tried it plenty, and when I actually manage to commit to putting everything into their boxes and folders, and putting those boxoes and folders into some space meant to hold it, it still ends up biting me in the ass and making it harder for me to get work done.\n\nWhy?\n\nBecause if I put all the shit I need to use for work into those boxes, those folders, those bureaus and bins, ''I will forget where they are, or that they exist outright.''\n\nIf you write, you want all your writing tools in clear view, even if that view is 'messy'. Same goes for making art. Same goes for just about anything, hell, even for the act of cleaning itself. The amount of times I've bought something like a pack of cleaning rags or more cleaning fluid only to find out days later we already had plenty, it was just buried somewhere in a closet or a cabinet or a box...\n\nIt's an awful lot. It's too much. When you can't easily see where something is, especially the tools you need or want to use every day, then those things will 'disappear'. It becomes too easy to forget where they are, which then becomes easy to forget you had them at all, which then becomes easy to forget what you were going to do with them. Or you end up spending money to replace things you already have, and put them into the same out-of-view organizational spaces as you did before, and they 'disappear' again. It's constant frustration and unnecessary frustration. We end up making roadblocks for ourselves by trying to organize things in a way that may work great for others, but creates problems for us and requires heavy amounts of brute force of will to get started to begin with.\n\nIf you've ever had a bunch of things in a highly visible pile - clothes on the floor, books and comics on a table, you name it - and you found you actually preferred things this way, no matter how much it might've confused and put off others, because "it just makes sense to me" or "okay, it's a mess, sure, but i KNOW where it is"... you know the kind of feelings with organization that I'm talking about.\n\nPerhaps you still want things organized, in a sense - it's not a bad idea at all. Rooting through something to try and find one thing is never fun. But you still want whatever it is you're going to use, especially the things you're going to use the most, to be very clearly and easily visible. One way you could think of it is the difference between how much more you'd use something that is within a closet in another room, and something that is in a transparent case that you see the moment you wake up every day.\n\nSo, when organizing your room, when organizing your workspace, do not prioritize ‘’Clean’’, not in the way as its been sold to us for our whole lives. Prioritize ‘’Visibility’’. The things you want and need to use the most every day should be easily visible and accessible. When you organize your space, think in terms of ‘field of view’ and ‘line of sight’. If you see a certain tool every day, and seeing it is very easy, does not require you digging through any boxes or drawers or cabinets, it drastically increases the probability that you will actually use that tool. It applies to more day to day chores and personal care too. You’re more likely to remember to brush your teeth when the toothbrush and toothpaste is immediately visible. You’re more likely to get cleaning done when cleaning tools are readily accessible and easily visible instead of being locked up in a closet. Hell, you’re even more likely to //change clothes// when clothes are easily visible instead of tucked away. Back to that example of ‘leaving everything in a pile on the floor’, how often have you neatly put away a whole wardrobe of options for clothes to change day to day into a bureau, only to either inevitably end up getting all the clothes back on the floor anyway, or wearing the same jeans and t-shirt for days, or both?\n\n(This is also why I’ve now often ended up putting clothes into big plastic buckets I can easily put clothes into, or pull clothes out of, instead of always into a bureau. Not the messiness of being on the floor, not the ‘out of sight, out of mind, has stopped existing to me, won’t remember that it’s there’ of putting it into a bureau. It’s not the prettiest solution, but good lord has it worked out well for me.)\n\nThere’s other things you can consider as well when thinking about line of sight and visibility for your tools. Color is a good example. If you’re the type always losing a tablet pen and panicking over having to replace it only to find it buried somewhere hours later, you might want to think of what you can do to make that tool ‘pop’ in your vision, and why it’s currently so easy to miss. Some of it might be ‘because it’s buried in with a bunch of other tools’, but think of how it might be blending with its immediate environment as well. If a tool of yours is black, and it’s surrounded by a bunch of other black things, and is on top of a black surface, then it might be of no surprise that seeing it, finding it, is harder than it should be.\n\nWhatever the tools are that you use, think about buying or modifying ones so as to make them popping out of their environment and into your sight, with color choices being one of the easier ways to achieve this. Bright colors in a dark environment will make those tools easier to find, easier to see in your day to day life. Using paint, markers, or brightly colored electrical tape to modify existing tools to make them more immediately visible within their environment can do a lot to reduce time spent looking for things and stressing about not being able to find them.\n\nBut whatever it is you need with your workspace, just keep that in mind whenever you organize or have to clean - think about ‘visibility’, not about cleanliness and organization as it has been sold to us. That framing does honestly help tons of people with their work, but its advice that so frequently doesn’t help //us//, can make things worse for us, and make us feel frustrated or like failures when those tips and tools do the opposite of helping us with our work. It may look bizarre to others, but when you prioritize immediate visibility and line of sight for yourself when arranging your spaces, I think you’ll find yourself feeling a lot less stressed out about the space you’re working within, at minimum.\n\n[[PREVIOUSLY: EXERCISE|exercise]] | [[NEXT: BASIC HUMAN NEEDS (FOOD, WATER, ETC)|basic human needs]]

<center><h1>THE KITCHEN TIMER</h1>\n[img[timer image]]</center>\n\nThis is probably the biggest, most important one for me, so it's the very first one that's gonna be covered. It also comes first because it covers a very important part of the process, the thing you have to do before you can even think about worrying about focusing on the task at hand at all. And that is, obviously but very importantly, starting the task at all.\n\nI used this technique to start writing this part of the twine at all. I used it to start developing this twine at all, not just for outlining what I wanted to do with it, but for even opening up the program and committing to the work at all.\n\nIt is the kitchen timer.\n\nThe inspiration for me on this method, unsurprisingly, comes from the Pomodoro technique, which is all about using a 25 minute timer with 5 minute breaks in order to keep consistent at work by breaking it down into short bursts over a longer period of time. And I've used it myself, with a fair amount of success! But this is about something more basic, more fundamental. It is not about working for a certain length of time, but for starting work //at all//.\n\nThe technique as I use it is incredibly simple. Get a physical kitchen timer - if at all possible it should be a physical timer. Not digital, not a program on your phone or your computer, a physical kitchen timer you hold in your hands and physically counts down time.\n\nThen, twist that timer to any point of time at all. I personally favor cranking it to the full hour.\n\nAnd... that's it. That's the technique in full. In terms of physical how-to, anyway. It's the mental aspect of this that is the most important to me, and also what separates it from the Pomodoro technique, especially digitally made ones.\n\nThe point of the kitchen timer as I use it is to, bluntly, switch your brain into 'do shit' mode. When you are looking at a chore or a task, or multiple chores and tasks, you've probably repeatedly found yourself in just //thinking// about those tasks and not actually starting any of them - even if the job at hand might be simple, might take a very little amount of time overall to complete. Your brain loops //thinking// about the task, but never gets around to //doing// it.\n\nThe kitchen timer's purpose here - as are many of the techniques and tricks I use - is to break that loop, to act as a tactile method you can use to circuit break your own thought process and force yourself to switch from //thinking// to //doing//. This is also why I heavily prefer a physical kitchen timer to any digital alternatives - physically turning the timer gives me a sensation I literally //feel// and can begin to mentally associate with "Now is the time to do shit". You're using how your brain builds memories and routines, how it comes to associate one thought with other thoughts, to create within yourself a physical-mental connection of 'When I turn this timer, now is the time to do shit'. I've found that the ticking of the timer also helps me an awful lot, providing a little bit of white noise to keep my mind occupied while I work. I'll go in further on how audio can be used to help deal with ADHD later.\n\nIt doesn't matter what point you turn the timer to or even if you work for that entire time or not. Your whole focus here is simply to shift from thinking to doing. I use this for creative and writing projects, like this twine itself, but most often I've used this technique to deal with day to day chores. Dealing with dishes or cleaning in general being the best example. I can spend hours and hours //thinking// about the chores I should be doing, about the dishes in the sink I should be taking care of and putting in the dishwasher, but so often do I never end up actually //doing// it... even if I'm in the kitchen myself, even if I'm standing right over the sink, looking at the dishes.\n\nUsing the timer, I create a physical and audio signal to my brain that now it is 'do shit' time, and pretty consistently I've managed to actually get those dishes done when I remember to use the timer. It also pretty much always ends up taking far less time than I'd expect or that I'd spent thinking about it. 5-10 minutes on dishes after spending hours having the thought 'do the dishes' in the back of my head. Then I can walk off and do something else, be it using the timer to do other chores, or just ignoring it and getting back to some personal enjoyment now that I got the necessary task finally out of the way.\n\nNot everyone will be able to use the kitchen timer to begin with, but this is also why I advocate with taking various techniques and experimenting with them and adapting them to yourself as needed. A disabled friend of mine couldn't use the timer, but they could flip an hourglass/sand timer. Not the same tool, but the same basic idea of switching the mind into a different mode - and they reported quite good results from it. Try other kinds of timers if necessary - I only advocate that, where possible, you use a physically based one. This will not always be possible! When it is not possible, many of the same basic ideas apply. You're trying to create new mental loops, routines, and anchors to associate one thing with 'time to do shit'.\n\n[[PREVIOUSLY: FOREWORD|foreword]] | [[NEXT: THE DIGITAL TIMER|the digital timer]]

<center><h1>THE DIGITAL TIMER</h1>\n[img[digital timer image]]</center>\n\n"Colin, didn't you just go on about how important a physical timer is to your own techniques and why you prefer it over a digital timer?" Sure did, entirely hypothetical person. But this is where we can see using similar tools for different reasons, approaching different problems with getting work done that tend to crop up with ADHD.\n\nThe kitchen timer I use to deal with "I can't get shit started at all". The digital timer is for a different problem of mine, living with ADHD: being unable to keep track of time. This, as you can expect, feeds into a lot of other problems, so tackling this can help stem the intensity of other issues as well.\n\nEven when I've successfully pushed myself into working on a task, there can frequently be the issue of //staying// on task - especially for a longform project that can take several days, weeks, months, perhaps even years to complete. We already know the struggle of having spent so much time thinking about doing something instead of actually doing it, but you'll still face problems yet of focus drifting off while you're supposed to be working... but more than that, you can frequently lack a general structured idea of //when// you should be working, especially when you're working at home or doing side, personal, or hobbyist kinds of work. You've probably felt the impulses of 'I should be doing something' at both 9 in the morning and 9 at night, and probably not least of which is because you've worked throughout the day, but probably in sporadic bursts. 10 minutes here, 5 minutes there, perhaps a half hour here and there, but sitting down and working on one thing for an extended period of time, especially when you're the only one holding yourself responsible for it... it's a real motherfucker, isn't it? Messes up your work //and// your recreation. While working, you think of fun you want to be having, while having fun you're thinking of work you should be doing, or so frequently, as illustrated with the problems discussed in the kitchen timer passage, you're not doing anything at all but thinking about these things while just shuffling around or staring off into space. You don't get a full satisfying session of work or a full satisfying session of play because you're either constantly thinking about the other thing you're not doing, or you're not doing either at all - and these problems are, of course, highly exacerbated in our capitalist hellworld.\n\nThe digital timer enters in to help deal with the problem that, for me, clocks are treacherous bastards, as is the passage of time itself. Having very little of an internal timer and almost never accurately guessing "How long has it been since I last checked the clock?", things get frustrating, to put it bluntly. Even when trying to use other techniques to put together specific blocks of the day dedicated to 'work time', I still found them coming up short. \n\nTry to say 'I'll work from 8-4 at home on writing, with a couple breaks and lunch, just like I would when I was at a big box retail job'? No good. I'm the one providing structure and obligations and deadlines for myself, and as awful and stressful as said retail jobs always were, they did have whole buckets of methods they gladly used to make sure I and everyone else stuck to working. I didn't want to copy those techniques themselves, since they'd just stress me out, and I wouldn't have the resources to copy them to begin with, lacking a boss or other things to enforce a clock-in or clock-out time. Not to mention that if I didn't actually start work at the time I said I was supposed to, then I'd just do things like 'oh well, now I can't start until the next hour, on the hour'. Lots of weird little shit in the brain coming up with bizarre rationalizations that ended up in less and less getting done.\n\nSo instead of trying to use normal schedule blocking for doing at home work, like "I'll work from 9-12", the framing in my mind becomes "I'll work for 3 hours". This is achieved in part by the digital timer.\n\nIt works just as simply as you'd expect - pick the amount of time you'd like to work. Given how much focus issues are a problem to begin with, I prefer not to swing big for '8 hours' and like to try with half that at 4 hours, or even half that at 2 hours. Either way, though, more than the kitchen timer can go up to. Then you punch that amount into the digital timer, start the timer, and... that's it. Again, physically quite simple, it's all about the mental effects of such a technique, especially if you start to use it regularly and it can wear a nice groove in your brain, becoming an easier to accomplish habit.\n\nOne of the little tricks here is that it's not actually necessarily all about //working the entire time// either, even though this tool is supposed to help with that. There are times where you'll still fail to get much of anything done, if anything at all! That's completely okay! Still happens to me! What the digital timer really helps do here is take back control of the time in your day. I mentioned how your mind can easily become split between thinking about work and leisure, focusing on the opposite when doing either of them, or ending up doing neither and just sitting there for hours - this is to help combat that.\n\nIt's not just getting the work done that matters, it is having specified points of time //for// work to make it harder for 'I should be doing something' to eat up your focus and energy while you're doing something else. Four hours of writing time for me that ends up with total writer's block is still helpful to me if I've specifically sectioned that time off //for// writing, and once it's done, I can more securely think 'welp, that's it for the day, onto other things'. The Pomodoro technique focuses on getting you to get more done in short chunks of time, but living with ADHD, keeping track of and taking control of the time you do have can already be such a struggle, and all the usual advice about how to do this is pretty much always aimed towards people who don't have the shit in our brain that makes trying to adopt those techniques feel like trying to brute force our bodies through a steel wall.\n\nWhen and where possible for doing things at home, look less to the clock, look less to 'I'll do this thing at 1 PM, and this other thing at 2 PM, and I'll start this at 3 PM and stop at 5 PM' and look more to using the digital timer to carve out specific chunks of the day as needed, even for oddball times like 11:46 AM to 2:36 PM. Once the time is up, pencils down, you're finished, move onto something else - again, when and where possible, I fully understand that there are plenty of circumstances where you won't be able to just go 'ah well, I'll get back to it tomorrow'.\n\nUsing the digital timer also applies to //doing things for fun// too! And not just for 'oh no I don't want to play too long and forget to do (important things)' reasons either, but for committing more time than one might usually to leisure. It might seem strange to others, but with my ADHD - especially in combination with other issues of mine, particularly depression - I can find it difficult to really set aside some time to have fun, to do things I enjoy doing, for my own pleasure. Focus issues, being scatterbrained, these effects aren't limited to 'serious' work, but it hits what we do for our own pleasure, too. As said at the top, you end up spending time thinking about the work you should be doing instead, but it's also easy to become distracted by all the other potential things you could be doing for fun and end up doing none of them. Or none of them long enough to really get enjoyment out of them.\n\nIndecisiveness while looking at a digital wall of video games you own, only being able to spend 5-10 minutes in one of those games before thinking 'what about all those other games I could be playing tho', difficulty sitting down and just watching a damn movie or a TV show because you could be watching other movies or TV shows or there's those games you could be playing or, yet again, there's work you could be doing... using the digital timer to create dedicated blocks of the day for your own specific leisure can be just as helpful as it is for completing work. For example, if you're like me and you //really// like RPGs but seem to really struggle nowadays to find the focus necessary to get more than 10 hours into them, then this method can be a godsend, especially when used in conjunction with other tools and techniques.\n\nThe digital timer lets you create those chunks of the day for various things in a flexible manner, starting and ending whenever you like, and not having to rely on the actual times of day to guide you which can be so difficult to keep track of to begin with. Getting back control of when you do work and when you have fun helps create more focus in both, spending less mental energy and time thinking about the other when you should just be doing the one at hand. Even if you don't actually end up doing much at all during that sectioned off time, you've still begun the road of taking control of that time, and that's the really crucial part.\n\n[[PREVIOUSLY: THE KITCHEN TIMER|the kitchen timer]] | [[NEXT: AUDIO VIDEO STIMULATION|audio video]]
